caption: A beautiful and tranquil place to sit and reflect. The entire building is a wonder and a fine example of stonemasonry, carpentry, and fine artwork. The only disappointment was a woman taking advantage of visitors who are likely to be charitable Christians. She was a middle aged respectable looking lady approaching all who were in the church asking for money because she had an unwell grandchild. I was not convinced of her genuine plight. It lowered the tone of what the building represents.

Paris, the city of light, fashion and artists. The biggest attraction is the Eiffel Tower, the Arc de Triomphe, the Notre Dame church, about which many movies and books have been written. The largest museum in the world is the Louvre and it houses many famous works of art, the most famous of which is the Mona Lisa. There are also the Champs Elysées, Versailles and the Seine River that flows through Paris. Mont Martre is where artists gather. Sacre Coeur church and Picasso and Dali once lived there. At the foot of Mont Martre is the Cabaret Moulin Rouge.
No ticket needed , even if I don’t understand French I stayed hearing the calming voice of the priest in a calming and beautiful environment
Very detailed and old fashioned church. With many paintings and statues of saints. Mass hours are available at the gates. And there ary many other activities and concerts. Worth a visit.
This church surprised us in the best possible ways. It looks simple from the outside but on the inside it is a masterpiece of woodcarving work and beauty. Just come by and take a look.

Just discovered it while walking the streets of Paris. Old Roman style architecture makes it look more like an old Roman temple rather than a church. From the street it does not look very inviting but it is a cozy and lovely place inside.
It's the most amazing cathedral I've ever seen. Incredible art, each time I can find/see something new. So meaningful!

Neoclassical church that sits right above the Metro.   The building is actually on pilings, because the ground is fairly swampy.   Because of the increased moisture--the frescos are created with wax and paint.   There are chapels at each of the 4 corners of the building, with one being darkened from smoke,  and another undergoing renovation. The organ is spectacular to see, and is well suited to the ornate surroundings.   An unexpectedly lovely church in the 9th.
Beautiful neighborhood church! And fun fact: This is where Claude Monet was baptized.
Mass at Sunday 9.30AM really fit my itinerary when travelling to Paris, beautiful church indeed. Even though the mass is in french, latin songs help me to feel involved in the mass
This roman looking church is quite odd in this city, this make this building even more appealing. This is a nice building to look, even the interior is simple, albeit simple

Notre-Dame lies at the eastern and was built on the ruins of two earlier churches, which were themselves predated by a Gallo-Roman temple dedicated to Jupiter. The cathedral was initiated by Maurice de Sully, bishop of Paris, who about 1160 conceived the idea of converting into a single building, on a larger scale.
Amazing architecture, and the decoration inside was really pleasing. The building itself is imposing and hard to fit into pictures!
Another of the very beautiful, but less well-known to tourists, parish churches of Paris. Beautiful art, frecoes and statuary
Unfortunately they were renovating this church at the time I was there.
